Movie Recommender System
Project Overview
The Movie Recommender System is a machine learning-based web application designed to provide personalized movie suggestions to users. In an era of infinite content, this system simplifies the discovery process by identifying movies that share similar characteristics with a user's favorite titles. Unlike collaborative filtering, which relies on other users' ratings, this project implements Content-Based Filtering, meaning the recommendations are generated based on the intrinsic attributes of the movie itself, such as its plot summary, genre, cast, and crew.

Data Processing and Engineering
The foundation of this project is built upon the TMDB 5000 Movies dataset. The raw data underwent a rigorous cleaning and transformation phase to ensure high-quality inputs for the model. Using Python and the Pandas library, I extracted critical information from complex JSON-formatted columns (like genres, keywords, cast, and crew). A significant part of the engineering involved merging these individual features into a single consolidated column called "Tags."

To refine these tags, I applied Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques. This included converting all text to lowercase to maintain uniformity and applying Porter Stemming via the NLTK library. Stemming was crucial to reduce words to their root forms (e.g., converting 'actors', 'acting', and 'acted' to 'act'), which prevents the model from treating related words as distinct entities, thereby improving the accuracy of the similarity calculation.

Vectorization and Similarity Logic
Because machine learning models cannot process raw text, the "Tags" column was transformed into a numerical format using Text Vectorization. I utilized the CountVectorizer (Bag of Words model) from Scikit-learn to convert the text into a 5000-dimensional vector space. Each movie is represented as a unique vector in this multi-dimensional space based on the frequency of the most common 5000 words across the entire dataset.

The core engine of the recommendation logic is based on Cosine Similarity. Instead of calculating the Euclidean distance (which measures the distance between points), Cosine Similarity measures the cosine of the angle between two vectors. This approach is much more effective for text-based data as it focuses on the orientation and thematic overlap between movies rather than just the magnitude of the data. When a user selects a movie, the system calculates the similarity score between that movie's vector and every other movie in the database, returning the top five closest matches.


Deployment and User Interface
For the final phase, the trained model and similarity matrix were exported using the Pickle library to ensure persistence and ease of use in a production environment. I developed the frontend using Streamlit, a powerful framework for building data science web applications. The resulting interface allows users to seamlessly select a movie from a searchable dropdown menu. Upon clicking the "Recommend" button, the backend processes the request through the similarity matrix and instantly displays the titles of the five most similar movies in an organized, responsive grid layout.
